vectorData.altText: 9. The two layers of the cranial dura are the ______________ and _______________ layers. (separate answers with one space)
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
That’s right!  Cranial dura consist of 2 layers: periosteal and meningeal layers.

Unlike the spinal dura, the cranial dura consists of two layers: the periosteal and meningeal layers. 
The periosteal layer of the dura is, in fact, the periosteum lining the inner surface of the skull. As it is anchored into the bone matrix by collagenous penetrating fibres, it is very tightly adhered to the skull.

For the most part, the meningeal layer of the dura adheres to the inner surface of the periosteal layer, forming a single bilaminar structure, the cranial dura. The exceptions occur where the meningeal layer of the dura separates from the periosteal layer to fold inward, forming rigid partitions that separate subdivisions of the brain. These partitions are called dural reflections. An example is the falx cerebri, which separates the right and left cerebral hemispheres.

Along the lines of attachment of the dural reflections, intracranial venous structures are created between the periosteal and meningeal layers of the dura. These spaces, which contain venous blood, are the dural venous sinuses. An example is the superior sagittal sinus.
